govname1: Hunt, Guy and then James Folsom Jr.
govname1_sour: Moore, John L., Jon P. Preimesberger, and David R. Tarr, eds. 2001.  Congressional Quarterly's Guid to U.S. Elections.  4th edition.  Washington, DC: CQ Press.
govname2_notes: Gary Hunt’s last day of office was April 22, 1993 upon being convicted for misusing campaign funds.  He was succeeded by James E. Folsom Jr. who previously was the Lt. Gov.
past_gov_note: James E. Folsom Jr. is not the same governor who was in office in the 1950s.
gov_midyear_change_c_note: the new gov came in before the budget passed, so midyear change is coded "1."
years_left_before_limit_note: New note from Excel file that was brought into this one April 10, 2011.  Because the budget almost always passes after Hunt was out of office, I'm coding this as Folsom being in office.
Lame_Duck_Notes: Because the budget almost always passes after Hunt was out of office, I'm coding this as Folsom being in office.

party_midbiennium_change_note: no problem for responsibility over the economy or budget.  New gov was in long enough.
govparty_c_note: On April 22, the gov went from R to D.  Since the budget almost never passes that early, I'm considering the gov to be a D for the purposes of this analysis.

govname1: Andersen, Elmer L. followed by Karl F. Rolvaag
govname1_sour: Moore, John L., Jon P. Preimesberger, and David R. Tarr, eds. 2001.  Congressional Quarterly's Guid to U.S. Elections.  4th edition.  Washington, DC: CQ Press.
govname2_notes: Elmer L. Andersen seemed to have won the election of 1962 but it was disputed.  The mn supreme court ruled that rolvaag actually won by 91 votes.  Andersen only served until march 25, 1963.
gov_midyear_change_c_note: the change in gov came in the middle of the legislative session.  I'll put in "1" for mid-year gov change, and keep new_gov_c "1" although I don't know exactly when the budget passed.
years_served_budgets_overseen_notes: I don't know when the budget passed, so I'm assuming it passed after the new mid-year change in the governor.
party_midbiennium_change_note: switch occurred early enough that this wasn't judged to be a problem for assigning responsibility.
govparty_c_note: The party of the governor changed on March 25 from R to D.  I'm not sure when MN budgets usually pass (I just know they passed on time).  Since March 25 is fairly early, and legislative sessions at this time usually ended in late May, I'll consider the gov to be a D.

govname2: Donald T. DiFrancesco-R, took over January 31, 2001, because Whitman resigned on January 31, 2001.

gov_midyear_change_c_note: the new gov came in somewhat early, but I'll still consider this a mid-year transition.  Furthermore, new_gov_c will be coded "1" because the budget passed months after the new gov.
fracleg_note_old_variable: The state house met for 33 days in 2001 and the state senate met for 36 days.  This means that 4/33 days the house met, and 2/36 days the senate met saw Whitman as the governor.  Those fractions are .12 and .06 respectively, so I'm putting in an average of .09.
stateleg_source: Conversation with state reference librarian revealed the DiFrancesco was the senate president before becoming governor.  The librarian got this information out of a book when I was speaking with her.

gov_midyear_change_c_note: since a budget was passed earlier in the year than the transition, 0s for gov_midyear_change_c and new_gov_c.  But next year gets a "1" for new_gov_c.
fracleg_note_old_variable: Based on the fraction of the session dates that Ridge served in before being replaced, and the codes of the two governors that served that year.
years_left_before_limit_note: because Schweiker took over in October of 2001, I’m coding this year as “1” because Ridge was the governor for most of the year
stateleg_source: Neither governor that served in this year were former legislators, so the code is "0."  See 2000 and 2002 on either side.
stateleg_congmem_notes: Based on the fraction of the session dates that Ridge served in before being replaced, and the codes of the two governors that served that year.
